video_title: The WORST GAME LAUNCH EVER #shorts
text: Hollow Knight Silksong took around 7 years. Clair Obscur: Expedition 33 took around 6 years. Baldur's Gate 3 took around 7 years. Helldivers took around 8 years. Lethal Company took around 10 years. Elden Ring took around 5 years. The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild took around 5 years. Anthem based on dev took around 2 years. Mindseye took around 2 years. New World took around 5 years. Cyberpunk 2077 took around 4 years. Fallout 76 took around 4 years. Star Citizen has been in development for 15 years.  What can we conclude? It takes around 7 years to make a game if we take game like No Man's Sky which was in development for around 5 years and consider they spend several years making it great we can conclude the 7 years is great example. Anthem which technically took 7 years clearly needed few years more if we consider E3 2017 as the time when they started making the game they needed at least 3 more years to make it good which looking at Anthem 2.0 looked to be the case but they closed the game.  a lot of games that come out rushed have 5 years or less development time and a lot of games that are great spend 5 years or more making the game. Triple A Publishers want to release game in 2 years and assume you can get that all done by hiring 10 times more devs but adding more devs does not mean the game gets done faster which they refused to accept.  Yes, you can make great game in 1 year but that would be exception which confirms the norm. I strongly believe games take roughly 7 years to make 5 at minimum and 10 at most with exceptions like Star Citizen which is suffering from feature bloat.

video_title: Why I NEVER Recommend Gaming Laptops #tech #pc #technology #shorts
text: Got the laptop I'm on back in 2021 to run rdr2, asked a friend (who I'm guessing didn't know what I'd learn the hard way), if it's specs were good and he said yeah they're really good actually it can run games even after rdr2  I knew something was off when I couldn't get playable fps on rdr2 if the resolution was at 1980X1280, I've got to keep it at 1280X720 to make it playable even then I can't keep the fancy setting at anything higher than low  But I kept moving, made good memories with it and was happy, then I played the yakuza series and at certain points it would just randomly go into sleep and id have to press the power button to turn it on again, then I got to Yakuza 6 and during the tutorial it just shut off completely trying to turn it on would cause it to make beeps and caps lock to blink but it fixed itself the next morning  Then I played like a dragon and the same issue occured, this time the ram had to be replaced  Would later go to a friend's house and his pc has slightly lower specs than my laptops, and he's able to run Yakuza 0 at 60 fos with 1980X1280nreoslution with every thing on max, it would be here I learned that laptop parts are smaller and thus weaker than pc parts, by alot. Heat is a factor aswell   And to think I thought I was so smart years ago for getting a portable laptop instead of a big and bulky pc. Oh how much of a fool I am

video_title: Why I NEVER Recommend Gaming Laptops #tech #pc #technology #shorts
text: Honestly while they are kind of cliche, Alienware with the full backing of Dell Premium Support isn't the worst option out there I have seen. If you take care of it, and it makes it through the first 3~+ years of life unscathed it should continue for quite a while. Same goes for ASUS if you are careful but don't get quite the same level of support if something does go sideways.  MSI I have always had mixed feeling about. Reasonably good bang for the buck on paper, but I can't say I have ever been impressed with their build quality nor long term reliability since they seem to go through their designs and model offerings like a pack of Costco Socks.  EVGA had a few nice attempts but sadly came and went so fast that there is nothing to talk about with them even though their build quality was excellent if a bit strange on their port selection and placement.  Framework really is going to be the disruptor here as you can fix/replace anything that fails and hopefully in time, get all sorts of custom options without having to fork out for a single spec you are stuck with that may/may not have everything you wanted. Hopefully their success leads to having a ton of optional upgrades and maybe even some other outside offerings can come in as well. Guess we will see.

text: I just personally don't understand them. Like, for a school application or perhaps a job where you bring work home, sure, that makes complete sense. but that's like, soft work stuff.  I feel like Gaming itself is not really ever going to be very viable on a laptop long term. It just makes them more consumable than a desktop for the same price. Especially when it's possible to play games without a laptop if you have a smart phone through various streaming applications, even going so far as to hosting your own entirely unattached from any company, Streaming might be a limitation, but it's a pretty decent trade off for not having to spend 2 grand every 3 years on a device you can't upgrade, you can't leave running and will literally cook itself to death if you use it as intended.  If more laptops were like Frameworks, that would be one thing, but the typical close ended minimized design of laptops is atrocious. You'd almost be better off stuffing a desktop into a briefcase with a battery tbh.

UE5 requires you to learn a whole new skill set of perfectly optimising almost anything in your project. And it honestly is annoying since most of the time since you can‚Äôt half ass it.  Also forgot to add that UE5 is MEANT to run at below 60 FPS if you‚Äôre playing ultra or cinematic.  Which is why devs in UE5 are supposed to focus on graphics or FPS. You can meet a good middle ground though, but ultra graphics are genuinely not meant to run at high FPS.

video_title: Nintendo Switch 2 VS Steam Deck
text: A more accurate comparison would be the 512GB Oled model since it is much closer in price.  It's also kind of a shitshow to set up things if you aren't used to Linux (although you should really learn if you aren't).  TBH, I don't find neither that appealing RN. The Steam deck is theoretically made to run 7th gens games and below and 8th gen games at medium settings at 40 fps. I don't really see the appeal without a generational upgrade that patches those into high settings and 60 fps for 8th genband allows better interface for better enhancements in lower gens. Since otherwise you are just playing mostly indies and older game rereleases. And at that point I would just get a switch and and if you really want something like emulators mod it for similar features and the Nintendo first party output. Which is honestly a better sell than the Steam Deck atm. You don't even need to use emulators for most games, you can just buy digital rereleases and these often come with gyro support build it which is also on the deck but you have to set it up yourself through Steam imput.  Respect Switch 2, it's pretty much just a Switch 1 with massive performance boost. Which basically trumps the advantages in the Steam Deck use to have in the games they share and have proper 1440p and 4k support through DLSS upscaling.  However, the Switch 2 games are a joke, but with game key cards making non first party output even more pointless than it already was. And the first party output is too early to make up for it.   So rn, I would say Switch 1 or even 2 is a better deal than the Deck, but that's because of how rocky it's OS is in it's current state and how the hardware was getting closer but not fully there for what they were aiming for.  A Steam Deck 2 which Valve is waiting for a proper generational jump to commit to can deliver the performance I mentioned before would absolutely smoke the Switch 2. Finally having the power to deliver the experience they always promised and likely with an Oled model from the get go.   I am probably over ranting on a 1 minute shitpost but I felt like doing it so I will anyway.

Meanwhile for 50 bucks more than a base SteamDeck (without dock) : Good, even excellent performance (though it depends game to game), 1080p120Hz display, detachable controller with internal mouse support, faster load time due to the SD-Express tech, included dock which boosts performance with a stable 4k60Hz output, still have physical versions (though there's some shady stuff but still, CyberPunk is complete with Expansion on a single cart). They are NOT comparable. If people on SteamDeck enjoy playing 720p30fps games, then they are just like people who enjoyed the Switch 1.

text: Eh. My steam deck has mouse and scroll pads, m.2 extensible egpu support, and I get better deals than gamepass by default in steam because there is always a sale. video_title: The First Xbox Handheld
text: After seeing that short clip with Linus with a bread again, makes me miss those days, Linus looks so great with it.  Anyways...  I'm glad Microsoft is trying to put in this effort, it took awhile, as there has many so many handheld Windows gaming PCs, which just didn't give a great experience, so naturally another company stepped up to base, Valve.  I'm curious on how well this will sell, as a hardcore performance PC gamer friend of mine, he refuses to buy the SteamDeck, but after this was announced, it was literally the first conversation we had, he's excited for it.  From this social interaction, I feel like this handheld might actually sell better than most people might expect, as both the Microsoft and XBox branding is in full effect, which a lot of hard-core gamers seen to have respect in.  I'd also be curious if SteamOS will be installable, or if since this is a Microsoft partner device, if they will lock down UEFI and SecureBoot making it impossible to load any other operating systems, as I'm sure super dedicated SteamOS and Linux users will try to install it on this device just to compare and potentially brag about some of the differences.  Does this new XBox handheld do game suspends and resumes like the SteamDeck?  As to me, that is a killer feature of SteamOS, as no other PC gaming system can suspend and resume so effortlessly like a video console, it feels almost magical to suspend a full PC game like that.  I do like the task switcher on this OS verses the more clunky one SteamOS has, so perhaps this release will further push Valve to improve SteamOS, as now OEMs have other choices, and if anyone knows Microsoft, they tend to get along with OEMs better than any other company.  Valve should really be watching this release very closely, as some of the feature sets are a bit better just from watching this video.

text: WHY can't someone make a game where the characters want their own stuff, which you can influence to a degree, but you have to work with them. And have just a modestly sized neighborhood where you can help it thrive but maybe you can brew up some drama and see the characters react to it... Sure, it's not easy to develop something like that, but it's also not impossible. Who wants shitty car driving in a game like this? That's a totally wasted development time. I want to be a "god" watching over a bunch of characters and nudge them to do things, help them along as they get older, maybe see them through some neigbor feuds and things like that. Go through realistic experiences with them. Watch as two families gradually start disliking each other and either nudge them to reconcile or instead throw more fuel into the fire. video_title: inZOI - Before You Buy
text: I'm waiting for the game to be more polished, but it does look interesting. I'd be interested in if they could have a gamemode that could use ai to direct the world rather then you yourself. Unique and exciting events would make inzoi different from the sims where no game can be played the exact same. Don't want ai voices, but behaviors and events to make the gameplay unexpected and at times challenging, would make the game more interesting. With ai, characters could make unique products and on somedays, your favorite store could be put out of business. The less control anyone has in the game's world building, the more expansive it could be. Also allowing the characters to have personal interests could mean that outside your control, your character may prefer one restaurant or clothing brand more than the other. This could result in a negative mood if they don't get what they want. A good realistic system requires discomfort outside the control of the player. If there was an option for an automated game world run by ai pathing, I believe the game could stand out more in comparison to better known games such as the Sims.

video_title: inZOI - Before You Buy
text: To me InZOI feels weird and sexless, by that I dont mean porn or whatever, I mean subjects and drama and human behavior that are born from things like that. As an example, in Sims 2 there was a guy who was cheating on his wife with the maid and they started you off with that, it was all very human, but InZOI just feels too clean... its like a place Captain Kirk would visit in Startrek, like some world that looks creeply perfect on the surface but deep down there is somthing worng with it. It could also be the slightly uncanny graphics that while better for me make it look unnerving in some ways, or the fact that Korea is hyper conservative so they cant really have and displays of human weakness in the game.   I know you can run kids over and cheat and stuff like that, but Sims 2 at lest felt like the game was designed to lure you into doing things like that, I guess Sims 2 is a test of human character but InZOI is a depiction of perfect human character, the only bad stuff you can do being things the devs forgot to stop you from doing.  Though, as a note, I understand alot of LGBT stuff is coming to the game, if somehow a dev reads this I would every much enjoy it if the controls that govern the population on that were placed in player hands... for... fun reasions >:) In fact all controls relating to the behaviour of the general population would be a lot of fun to play with.

video_title: inZOI - Before You Buy
text: I honestly feel like every Sims game since 2 (so yes, that includes 3) and these Sims competitors all suffer from the same issue. The focus shifted from telling meaningful stories, having meaningful gameplay based around the sims, their personalities and lives to this kind of soulless, meandering environment simulator. Basically these games all lack the heart that Sims 1 and 2 had and as long as these games try to cater to the masses by being as bland and customisable as possible, they will inevitably just appeal to casual players and aesthetes who just enjoy the visual and building aspects.   Sims 1 and 2 just had this unique quirkiness, depth and shock factor that is completely lacking now. It was depth focused over breadth. Nobody complained about closed worlds until we were spoiled with the prospect of open worlds but it came at the cost of becoming feature heavy yet lacking inner complexity. Think about the memory system of Sims 2.   Inzoi looks like it‚Äôs all flash but no substance. I would take a game that had 1/10th of the features presented here just to have zois who were animated, lively and dynamic instead. Why should we care more about how we can manipulate the appearance of the environments or drive cars if the zois themselves are utterly boring and devoid of the spark that makes them human and relatable?  I wish a game developer company would dare to make a spiritual successor to the early sims games that had a specific vision for the characters lives, rather than trying to garner as much mass appeal with the bells and whistles of ever expanding novel but ultimately useless features. Willing to sacrifice broad appeal for uniqueness and maybe even political incorrectness! But we seem to live in sanitised times where games like Sims 1 and 2 couldn‚Äôt be made anymore because we‚Äôre too preoccupied with trying to make everyone happy and aren‚Äôt willing to take risks and step on toes to make something truly innovating and inspiring.

video_title: game reviewers CRYING over no Silksong early access #asmongold
text: The issue is that, if there are no review codes, they have to rush through the game (and the writing, and the video editing) in order to get a review out there as early as possible.  That's a big reason why review codes and embargos exist. So they can complete the whole proccess withim normal working hours. No review codes, especially for a big release like this, means they will have crazy work hours  and will race to put out a review as soon as possible, even if it hurts the quality. (And their sleep schedules. ^^;)  That aside... I'm obviously not saying this is the case for team Cherry, but when a triple AAA dev refuses to give review codes or plave they an embargo until the game is release, it's usually a red flag. (Typically, the game is not ready for release, or it's just crap, and they hope to sell as many pre-orders and day 1 purchases before people become aware of a game's flaws.)  In Silksong's case the game is great, but... I don't think is a practice that should be celebrated. Distributing review codes (noth to traditional journalists and internet content creators) is generally a good practice.

video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: My experience with The Isle was absolutely terrible. I couldn't find any food anywhere - spent hours wandering around starving to death. The servers were practically empty with almost no other players to interact with, making the whole experience feel lonely and pointless. My gameplay consisted entirely of dying, respawning, and running toward migration spots that usually turned out to be empty or useless.  The lack of meaningful progression was incredibly frustrating - there's no sense of achievement or growth, just endless cycles of survival that lead nowhere. Every session ended in frustration rather than enjoyment. The encounters with other dinosaurs were rare and when they did happen, they were usually brief and unsatisfying due to the clunky mechanics and poor balance.  This video perfectly captures why I gave up on this game after wasting too many hours hoping it would get better. Save your money and time - there are much better survival games out there.

video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: This video, literally has me thinking and reflecting. About a game that I loved and grew up admiring its game ever since it step foot in existence. I have seen a few videos that have explained why the Isle is a terrible game. But even they combined cant match, the details Zenny has done. Which is very commendable, because a lot of what you have mentioned are topics that I have gone through but never took notice of it because I assumed that I am expected to find all this information out myself.  You have pointed out the flaws the game has, which can be fixed but seems like in the eyes of Dondi there is no flaw.   I do love this game, but heck. Those who play the Isle, really do reflect on the time you use on the game. I have 3998 hours in the Isle, that is nearly 167 days worth of playing a video game that doesn't save any hard progress you put, lots of players I know would disagree and wouldn't mind. I know some who have 5000+ hours in the game. It may not sound much, but that is actually a big portion of your life.  This video is an hour long, but it is 100% worth watching. (Make me wonder how much time you put in this video XD)  I remember when I first played the Isle back in 2022 for my first time. I had no idea what I was doing, I had no one to provide me support on what you are suppose to do in this game. I still remember, but I spent 3 weeks worth of time playing the game until I naturally understood on what I needed to do. (Bear in mind, I mean 3 weeks of me just walking around, finding food, finding diets. Dying, starving, falling. It was just me flushing time down the toilet.)  Makes me wonder about The Isle's future though, I do not even play Path of Titans mainly because it is difficult to even find, I do not know if I am looking in the wrong places. Doesn't matter, back to the Isle. What will happen to the Isle 2 years from now? I mean currently the Trike has been released, Rex and Allo are about to be released at the end of the month. Time will tell us indeed.  All the best for you Zenny üëè‚ú®

video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: "Am I doing this right?" 'BOUT MADE ME CRY. _BUDDY._ That's a whole ass mood.  I'm so happy that so much of this video was about the map. The fact that the map is so enormous while having so few people is a crime. I also read that AI only spawns when a certain number of people are in the region. (More people visit, more AI spawn) So, if fish are spawning in the river, you know people are around. That's something I learned from posts that were 2, 4, 6 years old on Reddit. _Reddit._ Not in-game, Reddit. I died like three times on a deino at that point, and now I was at ~45% growth and 0% diet 'cause I was playing solo. Yeah... they really need to change how the AI works. Solo isn't viable, and that's a load of absolute crap when you're on a map of that size with random spawns. Also, I'll never understand how people say the game is scary. The dark isn't scary, it's annoying. "Oh no, I can't see, what if there are monsters." Yeah, well, if I die, I won't see it coming, so whatever, kill me, I guess. I'll wake up and still be blind. Oh, wait, I won't be killed because there's _nothing there._ I'll go hours and hours--actual in-game days--and never see a single person. The very last time I played Evrima, I played for 3 hours in swamp as a gator and didn't see a single soul (died twice... give you a hint why), and the third time I FINALLY met someone and immediately got killed. Uninstalled beta. :) Just not worth it.  Also, I had legitimately no clue what any of those symbols meant in the smell bar, except sanctuary. I just knew sanctuary had mushrooms that herbis liked. I didn't know they moved! Crazy! See, this is what tutorials are for.

text: I'm a new player (I started playing a little over a week ago), and while I appreciate and agree with a lot of what was said in this video, I also think it's somewhat subjective. You might be right about there being a lot of bad game design, but that doesn't mean the game is no longer fun.  I've been addicted to this game since I started playing it. I see other people in this comment section talking about how the "community is dead" and "there's rarely any other players around," but that hasn't been my experience at all. Perhaps that's because I joined a very populated and friendly community server. There's always hundreds of players online at any given time, and because it's so populated, I encounter other players constantly. Due to the high player count, the server owners had to disable the npc animals. Even so, due to a well-balanced diversity of dinos on this server (and large total population), there's still plenty of opportunities for carnivores to get food. The server owners also take steps to balance the distribution of dinos and their behavior so bad actors can't egregiously disadvantage other players.  I only play Hypsilophodon, and I've been able to reach full-grown (well, reaching full-grown as a hypsil is easy, tbf) and nest multiple times. It doesn't take long for other players to hatch from my eggs, either. The same goes for groups I've been in where other Hypsils are the ones nesting. For me, the nesting experience hasn't been miserable at all. If anything, I'm appreciative of its realism. Animals irl have to deal with the vulnerability of limited food and safety when nesting.  It might be that being a part of a good server has made my experience vastly different from other players. I actually attempted The Isle years ago and had a terrible time with it; with both the game and the community. The game didn't explain anything (which is still an issue today), and the community was so unfriendly and unwelcoming that no one was willing to teach me anything either. It was only after recently seeing The Isle videos pop up on my feed that I became interested again. And this time around, other players were kind enough to help me when I was struggling, which also made me more willing to put more effort into learning more about the game myself.  With all the flaws and bad development choices currently plaguing The Isle, it's still one of my favorite games at the moment.

text: 22:39 I‚Äôve said this for a long time now that it feels like the developers are making a game for themselves in particular. With every product comes a target audience with the starting point of your own interest. You have an interest, inconvenience, something that warrants you to create for a larger audience so not only you can enjoy it, but everyone else. The Isle developers sadly take away that factor and cater to a very small population of the community that is agreeable with their decisions or an even smaller part of the community that complains the loudest. They ignore the rest of the audience, the real market, and then wonder why their game hits low player count or runs into issues such as losing once loyal players that they once had at the start. This issue exceeds their map design, but their decision making with certain playables such as making dilo as strong as it is due to a certain developer favoritism. Or how raptor faced numerous nerfs due to how popular the playable is and forcing the community to play other animals far more ‚Äúdesirable‚Äù due to their vastly more extensive kit or other reasons. I remember when raptor players took many hits, from it being mostly skill based with little luck to it being a whole lot of luck with skill assisting as crutches. I believe it‚Äôs at a decent place, but not nearly as good as it could be. Stamina is still a fairly large issue for the animal despite it being an ambush and pursuit predator, but lacks the sprint boost and, due to the stamina changes, can barely pursuit until 50% stam before needing to pull off. It‚Äôs a bit disappointing to see how many memories were made during Legacy and Spiro days, but how off-putting Evrima has become. I remember camping and spam joining servers that had over 300+ people joining at a time. Now the thought of logging on feels draining in it of itself.

text: "Old man yells at clouds" - Zenny.  I started playing during Isle_Region2 days. When you spawned you HAD to run to a watersource immediately or you would desiccate. This was when, when you first spawned you started with like 0% thirst. It was a bug, but it was brutal for a first impression. I pretty much stopped playing when Envirma was pushed to the forefront and I couldn't play it. The update in Legacy with nighttime that just straight up blinded you was not fun. I have a new computer now, but I'm not really interested in Envirma as it is, I agree entirely with the dino-size criticism. video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: I've been logging into this game once every 6 months for 9 years now. When evrima released it was pretty unplayable so I didn't give it a good try until recently. This game is like a toxic relationship. The good about it is unique to it. The minimalist approach actually simulates an ecosystem fairly well. The direction they're taking and the unique playstyles they're giving to animals is adding to this game what it was missing in legacy. The playstyles are the gameloop, and your choice of dinosaur is vital to it. The graphics make sitting down after stressful gameplay and enjoying the moment really fulfilling. The animals have individual personality, and you learn about their behavior naturally with time. The game evolves with simple changes like species dependent night vision. All good if the game worked. All good if pvp wasn't laggy, or if your card could pull the graphics. Or if the map was traversable with your fragile bones. Losing hours of progress to natural means is frustrating but good, but it's awful when it's because of bs. Maybe if they added sauropods or the like that would eat up everything migration zones would form organically.

text: This is such an accurate video... I've been playing since Legacy, and admin a (Previously very populated) server. I watched every painful step, and every poor choice. I saw the dedicated player base slowly lose interest after the maps were changed again and again while new playables were so delayed that by the time they showed up, players only returned to give it a try before uninstalling a week later due to game breaking bugs, no AI, and mechanics that were steadily getting worse and better at the same time.

video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: So I recently started playing the isle after watching videos from YellowTones. I liked dino games but I never got into them much before. I found a community on PoT and it gave me the confidence to try the Isle: Evrima. I really like the Isle, the aesthetic of the game and UI, it's VERY different than PoT but I don't feel one is better than the other. It's honestly more of a point of preference and mood. Sometimes I wanna play path and pester people (positive and negeative) on my Rhamph and have a good time. (I even got my hubby to play with me, we had a great time!) And other times I want to play Isle: Evrima. I have a comfortable pvp server via Metta's Den and a pve server via Life Breaks Free. And even there I switch. It took me about 50 hours of nearly constantly dying and playing with nesting players, before I finally found a dino that works for me. I'm a Herra but not the usual kind. I'm a peaceful scavenger. I can't really do the combat. I'm visually impaired and the darker lighting in the game makes combat nearly impossible for me. But I do have fun snagging lil bites of food from other carnivores or especially fishing on my pve server. Keeping a dino alive is really a joy with how awful the AI has been recently >.< Especially as you can't seem to kill any of it as a baby.   BUT and to the reason for my comment. This video was very informative and I agree with your assessment. I want to be a youtuber but none of the content I could get was worth anything. It was just me rushing to find food and dying. Or accidently killing myself, like smashing a Ptera into a tree. Or falling off a cliff as a Maia, woops. It was frustrating and a fair let down and nesting can be hit or miss. I really love it but after we've grown up, everyone tends to log off or leave which is a bit disappointing.  My main complaint for the Isle is (AI of course) but mostly, I want to be able to have multiple dinos. I don't want to lose the perma-death. I love the thrill of that and I think that's too foundational of the game. But I tend to only play on one or two communities and nesting happens a ton on various dinos and that's one of my favorite experiences. I want to log off my Herra and go run around with Troodons for a bit. Or get in on a canni skin raptor pack. But when my kiddo is home and needy, I really would like to be able to switch back to my herra, scavange when he's content and be able to partially afk in a gorgeous thunderstorm while I talk to or help him with whatever is happening. I am also an avid writer and being able to focus on both like my brain demands is really good and I've gotten really happy. Most of the time I'm not even stealing from anyone. It's just an abandoned turtle in the forest along the coast. Or a chicken someone killed but could never find. I'm not intruding on anyone, or griefing. I get the lil terrifying interactions and feel good about being able to survive. (Not so much dying to random starvation for no reason, I really agree, I wish we had the old spiro map back, that looked amazing. Honestly half the reason herra is so damn useful is because I can scale over these intrusive mountains in between me and critical scarps.)  Overall though, it was great to get some background on the game and understand why some things the way they are. And I am kinda curious where human vs dino is gonna go.

video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: When a survival game has to much stuff it gets boring and to much dificult. Many people play the Isle because they love dinos and want a dino simulator experience. I have played the isle for about 4 or 5 years and my thoughts on legacy and Evrima is: - To much time to grow a dino, some dinos are like 6-7hours to grow, and many times people die after 1-3h. -map is to big, we dont want a walk simulator, we wanto to ser other dinos, we want to herd, want to form groups. We are humans not dinos and we bring our biology to the game. Humans are social animale that need others to survive, thats natural to watch players forming groups to survive and stay in key places, we built cities near water we are not nomads we like to stay in a safe place with others, thats humans do so its hard to counter that. A huge map will be empty 99% of time. Servers with 100 people to a map that could have 1000 or more, the result is 99% of the map will be empty.  My opinion is have some good spots with lakes, with alot of food to haver herbs and carn going there to hunt. Make much smaller maps, make a few great places with alot of food for herbs and water. And make growth time a lot less, lile half to grow an apex or a huge herb.

video_title: Runescape Dragonwilds First Impressions "Is It Worth Playing?"
text: What do you think about exploration after spending a few more hours in the game? Personally, I found exploration quite enjoyable as I progressed through the gear tiers (which lets you access new areas). There are tons of item recipes to discover in hidden chests scattered around the world, some of which are tucked away in places that require you to do some improvised building to reach them, on top of using your powers. Some dungeons are hidden behind piles of rocks, completely invisible unless you try clearing the way first... overall, it feels quite rewarding for those who enjoy taking their time to snoop around and roam the world.  That's why I was surprised you mentioned it as uninteresting ;)

video_title: Runescape Dragonwilds First Impressions "Is It Worth Playing?"
text: My take is that it has a decent start, but not enough content to warrant its current price tag. it has a satisfying combat so far, and an interesting skill progression, my only gripe is they released it, without the magic or ranged skill tree available, i would have liked if they waited till they atleast waited till the game atleast had the core combat flushed out before releasing, dont get me wrong, there IS magic in the game, but its very limited, with most of its magic locked behind staves that take quite a bit to unlock and craft, speaking of crafting, it takes too long, you have to have next level patience to boil 200 dirty waters at 10 seconds a pop, especially when your character chugs water like their on the damn desert. the random dragon attacks gets annoying after a while, especially since you're essentially forced to hide whenever he appears and this can be kinda fucky when youre doing other things especially raiding areas where the enemies will obviously not just stand around while you sit in a corner praying the dragon fucks off. also optimization could use some work, but thats because most early access games are launching just to gain some initial funds.  overall its a decent start like i said, but i dont believe its worth buying right now, id advice to wait until they flush things out more atleast until the combat is fully out, because now despite magic and bows being in the game, theres no way to progress them so you're essentially forced to be a melee build. but if you really want to play it, cap'n jack sparrow got you covered

video_title: Runescape Dragonwilds First Impressions "Is It Worth Playing?"
text: I have to say it's a bit sad that you don't talk about any basic gameplay components that are just nearly unusable or just bad. Like every single cooking recipe, it needs at least two ingredients: 2 stakes, 2 chicken, 2 berries, 2 pieces of everything, which makes no sense and is an unnecessary grind. Saying crafting isn't as grindy is also a lie. I never had to run back and forth as often in a survival game as I did here to simply build a house. Besides, the building of houses feels terrible without the ghost mode. If you equip a weapon and shield and switch to one of your tools and back, your shield is no longer equipped with your weapon, and you have to do it on your own. You can't use your scroll wheel to switch your tools. In the game, you have to eat and drink as your character is never saturated. Not only does the combat feel clunky, the overall movement and jumping feels pretty bad. 600 people worked on this project, and the animations look worse than the animations from solo devs. The weight system makes 0 sense. While you need wood the most, wood is 4 times heavier than stone and 20 times more different to get. While playing the game, half of it felt like a log-cutting simulator. In the first minute of the game, you learn how to use your crafting table and how to craft weapons and tools. After you do this, you get the same tools in the next quests again. Some of the icons also feel like the developers didn't even think the tiniest bit about their game. Like the exhaustion bar is an arm? What the hell? Most of the game literally feel like the devs haven't played their game a single time and just want to use the runescape IP to make a fast cash grab. Even if it is an early access and of course, it will have problems. This is the worst early access survival game out there. And they literally want 30‚Ç¨ from you to test their garbage

text: Thanks, its really helpful to see legitimate gameplay, really helped me decide if i want to play. Some things you didn't go into (because you probably didn't know about them in pre-release sneak peak)  - Requires EOS account to play 'with friends'. EOS being a potential roadblock to even playing the game with how many problems EOS has. - Some skill trees are non-existant outside of a basic attack, like magic. (Perhaps these will come as they flesh out a still combersome combat system?)  For now, I can't warrant paying a steep price for a half-made game, especially given the major red-flags like requiring a problematic EOS log in to play online. Hopefully that gets removed in future as the game fleshes out, and will be worth another look.

text: I've played OSRS since I was a kid. Something I was talking to my childhood friend who got me into the game originally about last night was that I'd love it if at some point they added something similar to the Grand Exchange into the game so even if you may not interact with tons of people in your individual world, you can still have community trading. (Even better if they added gold to the game, obviously.) I can already foresee there being communities where people will make worlds people can join to trade rarer/harder to find items back and forth because you CAN take your entire inventory to a new world in multiplayer. Not your chests, but definitely your inventory. And that means you can help a friend just starting out to be more durable in the early game. There's a lot of potential for an economy just like in OSRS even if it isn't an MMO.

video_title: Runescape Dragonwilds First Impressions "Is It Worth Playing?"
text: they put too many RPG/Runescape mechanics into a survival/crafter. if spells are supposed to help with gathering then they shouldn't have a cooldown. or at least, a much lower cooldown, especially when they already cost a resource you have to gather as well. i get it's so you don't end up making the gathering tools obsolete but they can already feel that way especially later materials for mining which are found bunched together in nodes. just explode the node and it'll be about 40 seconds for you to make your way over to the next node, so what's the point of pickaxes then? think they need to make a decision on where they want to stand with that. before playing, i was under the impression they were going to be mage only spells, not just anyone can use them but i guess not. it would make more sense that way if you actually chose a class in the game and were limited to that classes specifications for gathering. a mage uses magic to chop trees and explode rocks but it's not as efficient as a warrior or rogue with an super high level pickaxe or chopping axe, type of thing.   combat is so barebones im actually shocked they wanted to show it as early access. melee "special" attacks feel worse than just attacking normally, as a rogue i do not like how dagger plays. maybe it's just early access and they have a lot more planned but right now it's so lacking that i opted to just use a bow. combat needs a lot of work and a lot more variety. i can see this game doing well enough to be up there with ark and palworld, especially the base building potential i've seen in the community already, but when you step away from that and loot at the rest of the game, it's just not it. good bones but it's only bones. and with the obvious Dauntless asset rips for characters and animations, i don't have high hopes those bones will ever grow any meat.

text: I totally see their vision here and if they can incorporate the main map and all of the lore, backstory for quest lines and keep the combat engaging I think they got something here. Watching the game my opinions changed from snarky to accepting knowing there will be dedicated servers. I just want the true essence of Runescape to stay as a forefront in this game. I understand it's going to attract a lot of players but reading comments like "can we just get mana plz" in Twitch chat is sad to see because Runescape helped inspire so many games and younger players won't care and essentially just want it to be Valheim or Enshrouded. It's a Jagex product and if they are bold enough to brand it with Runescape they better deliver this time and players should understand this is a game based in another games world. It's ironic because what people call RS3 is what they could have developed over time into this and we'd just be calling this Runescape and I'd be starting in Lumbridge.
